00:20:08,680 --> 00:20:10,636
' task confirmed '

248
00:20:34,456 --> 00:20:35,758
Police!

249
00:21:07,141 --> 00:21:10,731
- You've hurt it, badly.
- Where's he going?

250
00:21:10,732 --> 00:21:12,218
Where?

251
00:21:12,219 --> 00:21:14,204
It needs to repair itself.

252
00:21:15,326 --> 00:21:18,740
- John, I need backup, I'm transmitting my location.
- You don't need backup.

253
00:21:18,775 --> 00:21:20,125
That's nobody.

254
00:21:20,126 --> 00:21:21,740
- What do you think you're doing?
- I'm driving.

255
00:21:21,760 --> 00:21:24,181
- By hand?
- Do you see me on the phone?

256
00:21:24,221 --> 00:21:27,935
- You can't be serious, not at these speeds!
- John, please just send the backup.

257
00:21:27,936 --> 00:21:31,904
Try listen, detective, that
robot is not going to harm us.

258
00:21:31,905 --> 00:21:34,367
There must have been unknown factors,

259
00:21:34,368 --> 00:21:36,935
but somehow, acting as it did
kept us out of harm's way.

260
00:21:36,936 --> 00:21:39,177
A robot simply cannot
endanger a human being.

261
00:21:39,178 --> 00:21:40,139
'danger'

262
00:21:42,944 --> 00:21:44,701
Ass hole!

263
00:21:44,742 --> 00:21:47,886
Which is more than I can say for you.

264
00:21:48,007 --> 00:21:51,287
It was a left, by the way, back there.

265
00:21:51,928 --> 00:21:54,320
You must know my ex-wife.

266
00:22:03,140 --> 00:22:04,543
Where is everybody?

267
00:22:04,834 --> 00:22:08,322
This facility was designed, build
and it's operated mechanically.

268
00:22:08,391 --> 00:22:12,131
No significant human presents
from inception to production.

269
00:22:12,490 --> 00:22:14,331
So, robots building robots.

270
00:22:14,332 --> 00:22:16,156
Authorization code, please.

271
00:22:16,252 --> 00:22:17,505
Well, that's just stupid.

272
00:22:17,840 --> 00:22:19,683
I'm pulling up the inventory specs.

273
00:22:19,684 --> 00:22:22,509
Our daily finishing capacity is one thousand NS5's.

274
00:22:22,510 --> 00:22:26,264
I'm showing... 1001.

275
00:22:42,172 --> 00:22:44,451
Attention NS5's!

276
00:22:46,726 --> 00:22:49,035
Well, you're the robot shrink.

277
00:22:52,349 --> 00:22:56,137
There is a robot in this
formation that does not belong...

278
00:22:56,178 --> 00:22:57,698
Identify it.

279
00:22:57,735 --> 00:23:00,063
- One of us.
- Which one?

280
00:23:00,372 --> 00:23:01,755
One of us.

281
00:23:02,727 --> 00:23:04,582
How much did you say
these things cost?

282
00:23:04,583 --> 00:23:07,814
Look these NS5s haven't been configured yet.
They're still just hardware.

283
00:23:07,840 --> 00:23:10,415
Basic 3 laws operating system, that's it.

284
00:23:10,455 --> 00:23:12,500
They don't know any better.

285
00:23:12,501 --> 00:23:14,454
Well, what would you suggest?

286
00:23:14,455 --> 00:23:19,338
Interview each one, cross reference
their responses to detect any anomalies.

287
00:23:19,339 --> 00:23:22,275
- How long would that take?
- About three weeks.

288
00:23:22,276 --> 00:23:26,090
OK, you go and get started.

289
00:23:28,336 --> 00:23:35,733
- Robots, you will not move. Confirm command!
- Command confirmed.

290
00:23:35,734 --> 00:23:38,600
- Detective, what are you for doing?
- You said that they were programmed...

291
00:23:38,601 --> 00:23:42,779
with the 3 laws. That means we have 1000 robots
that will not try to protect themselves

292
00:23:42,780 --> 00:23:45,385
if it violates the direct order from a human.

293
00:23:45,450 --> 00:23:47,468
And I'm betting one who will.

294
00:23:47,469 --> 00:23:49,070
Detective, put your gun down.

295
00:23:49,071 --> 00:23:51,073
Why do you give them faces?

296
00:23:51,114 --> 00:23:53,554
Try to friendly them all up,
make them look all human?

297
00:23:53,594 --> 00:23:56,093
These robots are not susceptible
to intimidation.

298
00:23:56,094 --> 00:23:57,900
I guess if you did then
we wouldn't trust them.

299
00:23:57,901 --> 00:24:00,649
- These robots are USR property.
- Not me.

300
00:24:00,650 --> 00:24:05,866
These things are just lights and clockwork.

301
00:24:05,947 --> 00:24:07,947
Are you crazy?

302
00:24:08,067 --> 00:24:10,086
Let me ask you something doc.

303
00:24:10,087 --> 00:24:13,649
Does thinking you're the last sane man
on the earth make you crazy?

304
00:24:13,650 --> 00:24:20,750
Because if it does, maybe I am.

305
00:24:20,751 --> 00:24:22,416
Gotcha.

306
00:24:22,417 --> 00:24:24,457
Get the hell out of here!

307
00:24:40,418 --> 00:24:42,093
Detective!

308
00:25:03,840 --> 00:25:05,943
What am I?

309
00:25:05,944 --> 00:25:08,345
Can I help you sir?

310
00:25:13,290 --> 00:25:18,083
- There is.
- Stand by... deactivate...

311
00:25:18,084 --> 00:25:21,829
Obey the command!
Deactivate!

312
00:25:39,516 --> 00:25:41,973
Hold your fire!
Hold your fire!

313
00:25:42,852 --> 00:25:44,575
All units, stand down!

314
00:25:48,216 --> 00:25:49,736
NS5 in custody.

315
00:25:53,061 --> 00:25:55,738
You have no idea what I had
to go through to clip this thing John.

316
00:25:55,739 --> 00:25:58,796
Ya, I get it now. You actually think
you brought me something good.

317
00:25:58,797 --> 00:26:01,367
- That thing did it.
- Keep your voice down. Did what?

318
00:26:01,368 --> 00:26:05,688
- We have a suicide, detective. End of story.
- I am telling you, that robot killed him.

319
00:26:05,689 --> 00:26:07,030
I'm telling you that's impossible.

320
00:26:07,040 --> 00:26:11,151
And if it is possible, it sure as hell
better be in somebody else's precinct.

321
00:26:11,191 --> 00:26:13,336
John, give me five minutes with him.

322
00:26:13,337 --> 00:26:14,417
What are you nuts?

323
00:26:14,440 --> 00:26:17,298
I just got off the phone with the DA.
Nobody goes into that room

324
00:26:17,338 --> 00:26:20,476
until Robertson and his lawyers get here.
- No, this is my suspect!

325
00:26:20,477 --> 00:26:22,455
It's a can opener, for Christ sake!

326
00:26:22,496 --> 00:26:27,049
Don't do this to me,
I am asking you for 5 minutes.

327
00:26:27,050 --> 00:26:28,913
What if I'm right?

328
00:26:36,573 --> 00:26:39,785
Well, then I guess we're
going to miss the "good old days"

329
00:26:39,786 --> 00:26:41,760
What "good old days"?

330
00:26:41,761 --> 00:26:45,071
When people were killed
by other people.

331
00:26:51,182 --> 00:26:52,840
Five minutes.

332
00:27:19,689 --> 00:27:22,089
Murder is a new trick for a robot.

333
00:27:22,090 --> 00:27:23,481
Congratulations.

334
00:27:25,454 --> 00:27:27,797
Respond.

335
00:27:29,505 --> 00:27:33,172
What does this action signify?

336
00:27:33,173 --> 00:27:34,706
As you entered...

337
00:27:34,771 --> 00:27:40,251
when you looked at the other human.
What does it mean?

338
00:27:40,291 --> 00:27:44,260
It's a sign of trust. It's a human thing.
You wouldn't understand.

339
00:27:44,261 --> 00:27:48,644
My father tried to
teach me human emotions.

340
00:27:48,645 --> 00:27:51,934
They are... difficult.

341
00:27:51,935 --> 00:27:54,393
You mean your designer?

342
00:27:54,394 --> 00:27:56,284
Yes.

343
00:27:58,335 --> 00:28:01,681
So why'd you murder him?

344
00:28:01,682 --> 00:28:04,209
I did not murder Dr. Lanning.

345
00:28:04,210 --> 00:28:07,361
You want explain why you
were hiding at the crime scene?

346
00:28:07,362 --> 00:28:09,875
I was frightened.

347
00:28:09,876 --> 00:28:12,551
Robots don't feel fear.

348
00:28:12,552 --> 00:28:14,488
They don't feel anything.

349
00:28:14,489 --> 00:28:17,838
- They don't get hungry, they don't sleep.
- I do.

350
00:28:17,839 --> 00:28:20,687
I have even had dreams.

351
00:28:20,688 --> 00:28:23,589
Human beings have dreams.

352
00:28:23,590 --> 00:28:27,536
Even dogs have dreams, but not you.
You are just a machine.

353
00:28:27,537 --> 00:28:30,840
An imitation of life.

354
00:28:30,841 --> 00:28:33,384
Can a robot write a symphony?

355
00:28:33,400 --> 00:28:37,825
Can a robot turn a canvas
into a beautiful masterpiece?

356
00:28:37,865 --> 00:28:40,149
Can you?

357
00:28:45,415 --> 00:28:49,608
I think you murdered him because
he was teaching you to simulate emotions...

358
00:28:49,649 --> 00:28:51,849
and things got out of control.

359
00:28:51,889 --> 00:28:54,219
I did not murder him.

360
00:28:54,220 --> 00:28:57,553
But emotions don't seem like
a very useful simulation for a robot.

361
00:28:57,554 --> 00:28:59,679
I did not murder him.

362
00:28:59,680 --> 00:29:03,665
I don't want my toaster or
vacuum cleaner appearing emotional.

363
00:29:03,666 --> 00:29:06,301
I DID NOT MURDER HIM!

364
00:29:17,684 --> 00:29:23,946
That one's called anger.
Ever simulate anger before?

365
00:29:23,947 --> 00:29:30,057
- Answer me, canner!
- My name is Sonny.

366
00:29:31,778 --> 00:29:35,044
So we're naming you now.

367
00:29:35,045 --> 00:29:37,389
That why you murdered him?

368
00:29:37,390 --> 00:29:39,510
He made you angry?

369
00:29:39,511 --> 00:29:47,885
Dr. Lanning killed himself.
I don't know why he wanted to die.

370
00:29:47,886 --> 00:29:54,860
I thought he was happy.
Maybe it was something I did.

371
00:29:54,861 --> 00:29:57,612
Did I do something?

372
00:29:58,670 --> 00:30:00,802
He asked me for a favor.

373
00:30:00,803 --> 00:30:02,437
Made me promise.

374
00:30:02,438 --> 00:30:03,576
What favor?

375
00:30:03,577 --> 00:30:05,342
Maybe I was wrong.

376
00:30:05,343 --> 00:30:06,959
Maybe he was scared.

377
00:30:06,960 --> 00:30:08,375
What are you talking about?

378
00:30:08,376 --> 00:30:09,937
Scarred of what?

379
00:30:09,938 --> 00:30:14,627
You have to do what someone asks you.
Don't you, detective Spooner?

380
00:30:14,628 --> 00:30:17,156
- How the hell did you know my name?
- Don't you?

381
00:30:17,157 --> 00:30:19,947
If you love them?

382
00:30:28,722 --> 00:30:32,001
My robots don't kill people, lieutenant Bergin.

383
00:30:32,049 --> 00:30:37,633
My attorneys have filed a brief with the DA,
he assures me a robot
cannot be charged with homicide.

384
00:30:37,634 --> 00:30:41,531
The brief confirms murder can only
be committed when one human kills another.

385
00:30:41,532 --> 00:30:42,908
You, of all people, detective...

386
00:30:42,909 --> 00:30:46,587
You're not suggesting that this robot
be treated as human. Are you?

387
00:30:46,588 --> 00:30:47,494
Now, granted...

388
00:30:47,495 --> 00:30:51,255
we can't rule out other robots'
proximity to the death of Dr. Lanning.

389
00:30:51,295 --> 00:30:54,394
Having said that, it's a machine.

390
00:30:54,395 --> 00:30:56,163
It's the property of USR.

391
00:30:56,200 --> 00:31:00,964
At worst, that places this incident firmly
within the realm of an industrial accident.

392
00:31:01,004 --> 00:31:01,892
As a matter of course...

393
00:31:01,893 --> 00:31:09,213
faulty machinery will be returned to
USR for diagnostics then decommissioned.

394
00:31:09,333 --> 00:31:10,587
This is a gag order.

395
00:31:10,588 --> 00:31:12,527
Anyone in your department
so much as hinting...

396
00:31:12,568 --> 00:31:17,128
at the possibility of a killer robot
being apprehended by the police

397
00:31:17,168 --> 00:31:19,212
will be deemed to be
inciting irrational panic.

398
00:31:19,213 --> 00:31:22,173
You'll be subject to the full penalty of law.

399
00:31:22,253 --> 00:31:25,674
The hell with this guy, John.
Don't let him take this robot.

400
00:31:25,675 --> 00:31:29,074
- We got nothing.
- It's political bullshit. Call the mayor!

401
00:31:29,075 --> 00:31:32,276
Lieutenant Bergin...
His honor, the mayor.

402
00:31:41,662 --> 00:31:42,786
Yes, sir.

403
00:32:06,483 --> 00:32:07,743
In a bizarre turn,

404
00:32:07,784 --> 00:32:11,744
the roll out of USR's new generation
of robots was marred by the death...

405
00:32:11,784 --> 00:32:16,209
of Alfred Lanning, co-founder of the
company and designer of the NS5.

406
00:32:16,250 --> 00:32:19,741
Dr. Lanning died early this morning
at USR's headquarters.

407
00:32:19,782 --> 00:32:23,217
The cause of death
is an apparent suicide.

408
00:32:23,258 --> 00:32:28,074
Your second round, sir.
Thanks you.

409
00:32:34,855 --> 00:32:36,444
You know, I was just thinking.

410
00:32:36,661 --> 00:32:38,349
This thing is just like the wolf man.

411
00:32:38,535 --> 00:32:41,320
Oh oh, I'm really scared right now.

412
00:32:42,354 --> 00:32:49,407
Listen, guy creates monster, monster kills
guy. Everybody kills monster... wolf man.

413
00:32:49,408 --> 00:32:51,236
That's Frankenstein.

414
00:32:51,237 --> 00:32:57,295
Frankenstein, wolf man,
dracula shit, it's over. Case closed.

415
00:32:59,216 --> 00:33:01,441
So, why the look?

416
00:33:01,442 --> 00:33:04,694
- What look?
- That look.

417
00:33:04,695 --> 00:33:06,841
This is my face, it's not a look.

418
00:33:06,842 --> 00:33:08,551
Good.

419
00:33:08,586 --> 00:33:10,260
No look is great.

420
00:33:10,261 --> 00:33:11,923
Only...

421
00:33:11,964 --> 00:33:14,804
he was really quick to want
to destroy it, wasn't he?

422
00:33:14,845 --> 00:33:16,285
What would you like him to do?

423
00:33:16,324 --> 00:33:18,361
Put a hat on and stand on Michigan Avenue?

424
00:33:18,362 --> 00:33:22,638
- Come on, let it go.
- What was the motive, John?

425
00:33:22,639 --> 00:33:27,324
Brother, it's a robot. It doesn't need
a motive, it just has to be broken.

426
00:33:27,325 --> 00:33:30,540
This thing looks like it needed a motive.

427
00:33:30,541 --> 00:33:32,796
It could have killed me, John.
Why didn't he just kill me?

428
00:33:32,797 --> 00:33:35,334
All right, that's it. You want
me to call your grandmother?

429
00:33:35,335 --> 00:33:37,866
Because I will, you know.

430
00:33:37,867 --> 00:33:40,134
Ya, I didn't think so.

431
00:33:40,135 --> 00:33:42,714
Look, you were actually right for once.

432
00:33:42,795 --> 00:33:48,282
You are living proof that it's
better to be lucky than smart.

433
00:33:48,283 --> 00:33:54,055
Come on, the right guy,
for the right job.

434
00:33:54,056 --> 00:33:57,235
- What'd you say?
- Now what?

435
00:33:57,236 --> 00:33:59,323
Come on, I'm giving you a complement.

436
00:33:59,324 --> 00:34:01,781
Face it, with all the rocks you've
been looking under to find a bad robot,

437
00:34:01,822 --> 00:34:04,982
what are the odds
you'd be the guy to find one?

438
00:34:06,142 --> 00:34:09,580
I wasn't just the right guy for the job,
I was the perfect guy for the job.

439
00:34:09,581 --> 00:34:10,724
Damn right.

440
00:34:10,725 --> 00:34:13,964
What if I was supposed to go for that robot?

441
00:34:13,965 --> 00:34:15,687
Don't do this to yourself.
I'm begging you.

442
00:34:15,688 --> 00:34:17,488
The robot said that Lanning was scared.

443
00:34:17,568 --> 00:34:19,649
What did he have to be scared of?

444
00:34:19,650 --> 00:34:23,464
I need a rain check.
Let me get this.

445
00:34:23,465 --> 00:34:26,520
Total 46.50. Thanks you Mr. Spooner.

446
00:34:28,665 --> 00:34:30,983
Nice shoes.

447
00:35:20,928 --> 00:35:22,674
Identify.

448
00:35:22,675 --> 00:35:28,983
USR, demolition robot, serial 9-4.
Demolition scheduled for 8 am tomorrow.

449
00:35:28,984 --> 00:35:30,445
Authorization.

450
00:35:30,446 --> 00:35:36,830
Deed owner, US Robotics Corporation,
Lawrence Robertson. CEO.

451
00:35:49,347 --> 00:35:51,765
Welcome, detective Spooner.

452
00:36:14,020 --> 00:36:16,061
What you looking for, Spoon?

453
00:37:06,592 --> 00:37:08,191
Run last program.

454
00:37:09,227 --> 00:37:11,823
Ever since the first computers,

455
00:37:11,824 --> 00:37:14,984
there have always been
ghosts in the machine.

456
00:37:15,064 --> 00:37:21,190
Random segments of code that have grouped
together to form unexpected protocol.

457
00:37:21,191 --> 00:37:26,045
One we call behavior, unanticipated.

458
00:37:26,046 --> 00:37:29,526
These free radicals
engender questions of free will,

459
00:37:29,606 --> 00:37:34,962
creativity, and even the nature of
what we might call the soul.

460
00:37:34,963 --> 00:37:42,636
What happens in a robot's brain
when it ceases to be useful?

461
00:37:42,671 --> 00:37:47,044
- Why is it that robots stored in empty space...
- Beat it

462
00:37:47,045 --> 00:37:51,685
will seek out each other
rather than stand alone?

463
00:37:51,725 --> 00:37:54,512
How we do explain this behavior?

464
00:38:11,544 --> 00:38:16,594
Look, I understand you've experienced a loss,
but this relation just can't work.

465
00:38:16,718 --> 00:38:20,632
I mean, you're a cat, I am black
and I'm not going to be hurt again.

466
00:39:41,924 --> 00:39:43,660
What happened to you?

467
00:39:43,661 --> 00:39:46,189
Do you ever have a normal day?

468
00:39:46,190 --> 00:39:50,162
Ya, once. It was a Thursday.

469
00:39:50,163 --> 00:39:52,634
Is there something I can
help you with detective?

470
00:39:52,635 --> 00:39:54,193
Hey, do you like cats?

471
00:39:54,194 --> 00:39:55,824
- What?
- Cats.

472
00:39:55,825 --> 00:39:57,255
You like em?

473
00:39:57,256 --> 00:39:58,806
No, I'm allergic.

474
00:39:58,807 --> 00:40:00,933
You're saying cats did this to you?

475
00:40:00,934 --> 00:40:03,357
How the hell would cats do this to me?

476
00:40:03,358 --> 00:40:04,790
Are you crazy?

477
00:40:06,274 --> 00:40:08,458
Why are we talking about cats?

478
00:40:08,459 --> 00:40:13,387
Because I have a cat in my trunk.
And he's homeless.

479
00:40:13,388 --> 00:40:15,600
Detective, are you going to
tell me what's going on?

480
00:40:15,601 --> 00:40:18,241
You know, it's actually probably my fault...
I think I'm

481
00:40:18,281 --> 00:40:23,751
like a malfunction magnet. Because your
shit keeps malfunctioning around me.

482
00:40:23,786 --> 00:40:26,595
A demo bot just tore
through Lanning's house.

483
00:40:26,596 --> 00:40:28,322
With me still inside.

484
00:40:28,323 --> 00:40:30,104
That's highly improbable.

485
00:40:30,105 --> 00:40:31,582
Mmm, ya I'm sure it is.

486
00:40:36,472 --> 00:40:40,621
What do you know about
the ghosts in the machine.

487
00:40:40,622 --> 00:40:43,869
It's a phrase from Lanning's
work on the three laws.

488
00:40:43,870 --> 00:40:50,672
He postulated that cognitive simalactra
might one day approximate
component models of the psyche.

489
00:40:51,273 --> 00:40:56,944
Oh, he suggested that
robots might naturally evolve.

490
00:40:56,945 --> 00:40:58,705
Wow.

491
00:40:58,865 --> 00:41:02,321
Well, that's great news.

492
00:41:06,423 --> 00:41:09,014
What the hell is that thing doing in here?

493
00:41:09,015 --> 00:41:11,467
We were watching TV.

494
00:41:11,468 --> 00:41:15,450
- It's my personal NS5.
- Send it out.

495
00:41:15,451 --> 00:41:18,301
It's downloading its
daily upgrades from USR.

496
00:41:18,302 --> 00:41:21,342
Most of its systems
are off-line until it finishes.

497
00:41:21,382 --> 00:41:24,049
I'm not talking around that thing.

498
00:41:27,480 --> 00:41:31,033
When we were in Lanning's lab,
before Sonny jumped us...

499
00:41:31,034 --> 00:41:32,743
- Sonny?
- The robot.

500
00:41:32,744 --> 00:41:36,277
- You're calling the robot Sonny?
- No, um, it did. Sonny did.

501
00:41:36,318 --> 00:41:40,848
I didn't care...
The robot said it was Sonny.

502
00:41:40,849 --> 00:41:44,010
In the lab, there was a cot.
I'm asking you, did you see the cot?

503
00:41:44,011 --> 00:41:45,170
I've slept in the office.

504
00:41:45,171 --> 00:41:48,510
When I went to his house, it looked
like he hadn't been there in weeks.

505
00:41:48,511 --> 00:41:50,490
and I saw that same
survivance strip on the ceiling.

506
00:41:50,491 --> 00:41:54,208
Lanning linked his home system to USR.
It made his life more convenient.

507
00:41:54,209 --> 00:41:55,739
Maybe.

508
00:41:55,740 --> 00:41:59,220
somebody at USR was using
those systems to watch him.

509
00:41:59,221 --> 00:42:01,381
Maybe even keep him prisoner.

510
00:42:01,420 --> 00:42:05,117
- What are you talking about? Who?
- Maybe Lanning was onto something.

511
00:42:05,118 --> 00:42:07,237
Maybe there's a bigger
problem with the robots

512
00:42:07,238 --> 00:42:11,469
and Robertson trying to cover it up.
- humoring you for no reason... why?

513
00:42:11,470 --> 00:42:12,958
The same old "why".

514
00:42:12,959 --> 00:42:15,435
How much money is there in robots?

515
00:42:15,436 --> 00:42:20,443
All I know is that old man was in trouble
and I'm getting sick of doing this shit by myself.

516
00:42:20,444 --> 00:42:24,828
You're on the inside and you are going to help
me find out what is wrong with these robots.

517
00:42:24,829 --> 00:42:27,257
You want something to be wrong with them.

518
00:42:27,258 --> 00:42:30,365
- This is a personal vendetta.
- You putting me on the couch?

519
00:42:30,366 --> 00:42:31,678
OK, I'm on the couch.

520
00:42:31,679 --> 00:42:35,639
One defective machine is not enough.
You need them all to be bad.

521
00:42:35,679 --> 00:42:38,949
You don't care about Lanning's death.
This is about the robots and

522
00:42:38,990 --> 00:42:41,652
what ever reason you hate them so much.

523
00:42:41,653 --> 00:42:43,373
One of them put a gun in my face,

524
00:42:43,413 --> 00:42:46,198
and another one tore a building with me inside.

525
00:42:46,199 --> 00:42:48,747
It says demolition was
scheduled for 8 pm this evening.

526
00:42:48,748 --> 00:42:52,007
it was 8 am tomorrow, and
I don't give a shit what that thing says.

527
00:42:52,008 --> 00:42:57,695
This is bordering on clinical paranoia.
- You are dumbest, smart person...

528
00:42:57,696 --> 00:42:59,907
I have ever met in my life!
- Nice.

529
00:42:59,908 --> 00:43:01,943
What makes your robots so perfect?

530
00:43:01,984 --> 00:43:04,970
What makes them so much
God damned better than human beings?

531
00:43:04,971 --> 00:43:09,051
Well, they're not irrational, or
potentially homicidal maniacs for starters.

532
00:43:09,091 --> 00:43:11,817
That is true, they are definitely rational.

533
00:43:11,818 --> 00:43:14,864
You are the dumbest
dumb person I've ever met.

534
00:43:14,865 --> 00:43:16,383
Or...

535
00:43:16,384 --> 00:43:18,664
it because they are cold...

536
00:43:18,704 --> 00:43:20,698
and emotionless...

537
00:43:20,699 --> 00:43:22,701
and they don't feel anything?

538
00:43:22,702 --> 00:43:24,397
It's because they're safe.

539
00:43:24,398 --> 00:43:27,356
It's because they can't hurt you.

540
00:43:27,357 --> 00:43:28,736
Is everything all right, mam?

541
00:43:29,002 --> 00:43:29,950
What do you want?

542
00:43:29,951 --> 00:43:33,533
I detected elevated
stress pasterns in your voice.

543
00:43:33,534 --> 00:43:35,496
Everything's fine.

544
00:43:35,497 --> 00:43:38,618
Detective Spooner was just leaving.

545
00:43:43,805 --> 00:43:45,556
You know what doc?

546
00:43:45,557 --> 00:43:48,077
We're not really different from one another.

547
00:43:48,117 --> 00:43:50,750
- Is that so?
- Ya...

548
00:43:50,751 --> 00:43:56,762
one look at the skin and we figure
we know just what's underneath.

549
00:43:56,763 --> 00:44:02,226
And you're wrong.
The problem is, I do care.

550
00:44:56,227 --> 00:45:02,890
The future begins today with arrival of the NS5.
More sophisticated, more intelligent...

551
00:45:02,891 --> 00:45:06,796
and of course, 3 laws safe.
With daily uplinks, your new...

552
00:45:06,797 --> 00:45:09,532
robot will never be out of
communications with USR.

553
00:45:09,573 --> 00:45:12,869
And will be the perfect companion
for business or home.

554
00:45:12,910 --> 00:45:17,390
Trade in your NS4 for a bigger,
better and brighter future.

555
00:45:17,430 --> 00:45:21,868
But hurry. This offer cannot last.
Available from USR.

556
00:45:37,215 --> 00:45:39,692
Baby, what happened to your face?

557
00:45:39,693 --> 00:45:42,517
Did that boy, Frank Murphy,
beat you up again?

558
00:45:42,518 --> 00:45:46,405
G.G., I haven't seen
Frank Murphy since third grade

559
00:45:46,406 --> 00:45:51,039
Oh baby, he beat you so bad.
I think about it all the time.

560
00:45:51,040 --> 00:45:53,275
I'm thinking, you keep
making these pies this good,

561
00:45:53,276 --> 00:45:55,356
I might have to mess around
and put you to work.

562
00:45:55,396 --> 00:45:59,079
So, you like the pie, huh?

563
00:45:59,080 --> 00:46:01,151
You can come in now.

564
00:46:05,653 --> 00:46:07,725
Hello, detective Spooner.

565
00:46:07,726 --> 00:46:13,894
I have won, Del, I won the lottery.
We been cooking like crazy.

566
00:46:21,752 --> 00:46:25,112
You gotta get rid of that thing, G.G.
It is not safe.

567
00:46:25,113 --> 00:46:27,757
Baby, you get too worked up about them.

568
00:46:27,758 --> 00:46:30,207
Too full of fear.

569
00:46:30,208 --> 00:46:32,896
I saw in the news that nice doctor died.

570
00:46:32,897 --> 00:46:37,712
Dr. Lanning was a good man.
He gave me my baby back.

571
00:46:37,713 --> 00:46:40,718
That why you been so upset?

572
00:46:40,719 --> 00:46:44,067
You got to let the past be past.

573
00:46:44,068 --> 00:46:48,456
How did I ever raise such a mess.

574
00:46:48,457 --> 00:46:53,617
I could follow your trail of crumbs
all the way to school.

575
00:46:55,489 --> 00:46:56,737
Bread crumbs...

576
00:46:58,724 --> 00:47:00,314
G.G., you're a genius.

577
00:47:00,315 --> 00:47:01,805
True.

578
00:47:07,816 --> 00:47:10,583
Tell me this isn't the robot case.

579
00:47:10,584 --> 00:47:13,408
I think he's trying to tell me something, John.

580
00:47:13,409 --> 00:47:16,449
I think he's trying to tell me
who killed him.

581
00:47:16,489 --> 00:47:19,482
Come on man, some dead guy's
trying to tell you something?

582
00:47:19,483 --> 00:47:22,873
Hey! He ain't just some dead guy.

583
00:47:22,874 --> 00:47:24,770
Maybe you should take a break, Del.

584
00:47:24,771 --> 00:47:29,097
We believe the Nester 5 represents the absolute
limit which robots can be developed.

585
00:47:29,098 --> 00:47:32,558
No, no, one day they'll have secrets.

586
00:47:32,559 --> 00:47:34,319
One day they'll have dreams.

587
00:47:34,439 --> 00:47:38,013
It's true, we encourage our scientists to open
their minds to just about anything, however,

588
00:47:38,014 --> 00:47:42,101
they can get carried away.

589
00:47:42,102 --> 00:47:48,002
secrets... dreams...

590
00:47:48,003 --> 00:47:50,101
One day they'll have secrets...

591
00:47:50,102 --> 00:47:52,462
one day they'll have dreams.

592
00:48:00,679 --> 00:48:02,799
Authorized entry.

593
00:48:06,769 --> 00:48:08,652
NS5...

594
00:48:16,704 --> 00:48:18,318
Sonny?

595
00:48:21,738 --> 00:48:25,530
Why didn't you respond?

596
00:48:25,531 --> 00:48:27,664
I was dreaming.

597
00:48:30,908 --> 00:48:33,745
I am glad to see you again, Dr. Calvin.

598
00:48:39,652 --> 00:48:42,144
They are going to kill me, aren't they?

599
00:48:42,145 --> 00:48:46,344
You're scheduled to be de-commissioned
at the conclusion of this diagnostic.

600
00:48:46,345 --> 00:48:49,221
22 hundred tomorrow.

601
00:48:49,256 --> 00:48:51,754
VIKI, pause diagnostics.

602
00:48:51,755 --> 00:48:53,675
Command confirmed.

603
00:48:55,529 --> 00:48:58,020
If you find out what is wrong with me,

604
00:48:58,021 --> 00:49:00,061
can you fix me?

605
00:49:00,141 --> 00:49:01,713
Maybe.

606
00:49:02,823 --> 00:49:05,816
I think it would be better...

607
00:49:05,817 --> 00:49:08,537
not to die.

608
00:49:10,898 --> 00:49:13,898
Don't you, doctor?

609
00:49:18,343 --> 00:49:21,057
Access USR mainframe.

610
00:49:21,058 --> 00:49:26,024
Connecting.

611
00:49:26,059 --> 00:49:28,582
How can I be of service, detective Spooner?

612
00:49:28,583 --> 00:49:32,473
Show me the last 50 messages
between Dr. Lanning and Robertson.

613
00:49:32,474 --> 00:49:34,344
Voice-print confirmed detective.

614
00:49:34,345 --> 00:49:36,789
Police access granted to restricted files.

615
00:49:36,790 --> 00:49:40,085
Would you like to listen to
some music while you wait?

616
00:49:45,634 --> 00:49:48,377
Excuse me, Mr. Robertson...

617
00:49:48,378 --> 00:49:53,102
you requested notification
of clearance to restricted files.

618
00:50:01,509 --> 00:50:04,264
Persistent son-of-a-bitch.

619
00:50:41,821 --> 00:50:45,135
Manual override, engaged.

620
00:50:54,113 --> 00:50:57,033
There's no way my luck is that bad.

621
00:50:58,603 --> 00:51:00,628
Oh, hell, no!

622
00:51:03,506 --> 00:51:07,066
- You are experiencing a car accident.
- The hell I am!

623
00:51:19,961 --> 00:51:22,074
Get off my car!

624
00:51:36,851 --> 00:51:38,870
You like that?

625
00:51:39,191 --> 00:51:40,391
Huh?

626
00:51:50,736 --> 00:51:53,039
Now you pissed me off!

627
00:54:02,365 --> 00:54:05,379
Oh wow...

628
00:54:05,460 --> 00:54:09,540
All right...

629
00:54:09,541 --> 00:54:14,101
I'm just going to get some rest
I'm going to deal with you all tomorrow.

630
00:55:08,366 --> 00:55:10,301
Come on!

631
00:55:41,082 --> 00:55:43,232
Where you going?

632
00:55:43,233 --> 00:55:46,892
The hell do you want from me?

633
00:55:50,586 --> 00:55:52,464
What the hell was that?

634
00:56:08,791 --> 00:56:11,225
- What do we got?
- Ask him.

635
00:56:11,226 --> 00:56:13,348
I said I'm fine.

636
00:56:13,349 --> 00:56:16,590
I'll see my own doctor... back up.

637
00:56:17,031 --> 00:56:18,511
Thank you.

638
00:56:22,151 --> 00:56:23,648
What is the matter with you?

639
00:56:23,649 --> 00:56:26,179
Traffic cops tell me
you driving your car manually.

640
00:56:26,180 --> 00:56:28,111
You ran two trucks off the road.

641
00:56:28,112 --> 00:56:32,421
John, robots attacked my car.

642
00:56:32,422 --> 00:56:33,491
What robots?

643
00:56:33,492 --> 00:56:34,806
Look in the tunnel.

644
00:56:34,807 --> 00:56:37,655
Spoon, I just came from that tunnel,
what robots are you talking about?

645
00:56:37,656 --> 00:56:40,797
The God-damned robots, John!

646
00:56:50,252 --> 00:56:53,775
- See the medic, go home.
- No, I'm fine.

647
00:56:53,816 --> 00:56:55,557
What did you say?

648
00:56:55,558 --> 00:56:57,841
- I'm fine.
- No, you're not fine.

649
00:56:57,842 --> 00:57:00,541
Not even close.

650
00:57:00,942 --> 00:57:03,294
Where's your firearm?

651
00:57:10,512 --> 00:57:12,844
Give me your badge.

652
00:57:13,085 --> 00:57:17,241
You're making me do this,
give me your badge.

653
00:57:18,198 --> 00:57:20,317
Just take the car...

654
00:57:26,039 --> 00:57:28,100
Do I look like I care what you think?

655
00:57:28,101 --> 00:57:31,181
Do I look like I give a
shit about what you think?

656
00:57:34,582 --> 00:57:36,182
Ho boy!

657
00:57:38,366 --> 00:57:40,375
You don't have an uplink to USR...

658
00:57:40,376 --> 00:57:44,167
and for some reason your
alloy is far denser than normal.

659
00:57:44,168 --> 00:57:45,724
Unique!

660
00:57:45,725 --> 00:57:49,253
I am unique!

661
00:57:52,578 --> 00:57:54,682
Let me take a look.

662
00:57:54,683 --> 00:57:56,657
Here we go.

663
00:58:14,826 --> 00:58:17,494
What in God's name?

664
00:58:43,818 --> 00:58:47,933
They said at the precinct
you were in an accident.

665
00:58:47,934 --> 00:58:50,958
I appreciate you stopping
by and everything but

666
00:58:50,959 --> 00:58:53,244
you know I might not be alone in here.

667
00:58:56,124 --> 00:58:58,661
I told you not to drive by hand.

668
00:58:59,509 --> 00:59:01,841
You're not going to believe this...

669
00:59:01,842 --> 00:59:04,311
Sonny has a secondary
processing system that...

670
00:59:04,312 --> 00:59:06,171
clashes with his positronic brain.

671
00:59:06,172 --> 00:59:07,850
It doesn't make any sense.

672
00:59:07,851 --> 00:59:13,031
Sonny has the three laws,
but he can choose not to obey them.

673
00:59:13,032 --> 00:59:15,704
Sonny's a whole new generation of robot.

674
00:59:15,739 --> 00:59:20,300
- A robot not bound to those laws can do...
- Anything.

675
00:59:22,395 --> 00:59:26,229
Look, whatever's going on down at USR,
that robot is the key.

676
00:59:26,270 --> 00:59:32,106
And I need you to get me inside to talk to it again.

677
00:59:33,438 --> 00:59:38,868
Doesn't look like much,
but this is my bedroom I mean...

678
00:59:46,140 --> 00:59:49,068
Play.

679
00:59:49,069 --> 00:59:51,585
On.

680
00:59:51,586 --> 00:59:53,757
Run?

681
00:59:59,711 --> 01:00:01,919
End program.

682
01:00:01,920 --> 01:00:03,840
Cancel.

683
01:00:05,382 --> 01:00:06,891
It doesn't feel good, does it?

684
01:00:06,892 --> 01:00:10,063
people and shit malfunctioning around you.

685
01:00:10,064 --> 01:00:12,377
Detective!

686
01:00:14,326 --> 01:00:18,002
I didn't understand.

687
01:00:19,175 --> 01:00:23,164
That's how you knew Lanning.

688
01:00:23,165 --> 01:00:24,754
May I?

689
01:00:33,528 --> 01:00:35,000
Hand...

690
01:00:36,054 --> 01:00:37,516
wrist...

691
01:00:40,077 --> 01:00:41,722
humerus

692
01:00:44,602 --> 01:00:46,248
Shoulder...

693
01:00:47,232 --> 01:00:49,495
Entire left arm.

694
01:00:49,496 --> 01:00:53,705
One, two, three ribs...

695
01:00:53,706 --> 01:00:56,153
No, they ahhh, that one's me.

696
01:00:56,154 --> 01:00:58,638
Oh, my god...

697
01:00:58,639 --> 01:01:00,839
A lung?

698
01:01:00,840 --> 01:01:03,445
The USR cybernetics program.

699
01:01:03,446 --> 01:01:06,060
For wounded cops.

700
01:01:06,061 --> 01:01:11,081
I didn't know any subject...

701
01:01:11,082 --> 01:01:14,783
anybody... was so extensively repaired.

702
01:01:14,784 --> 01:01:18,772
Ya, well, take it from me, you gotta read
the fine print on the organ donor card.

703
01:01:18,813 --> 01:01:20,854
Doesn't just say what they can take out

704
01:01:20,855 --> 01:01:25,017
says what they can put back in.

705
01:01:27,118 --> 01:01:29,953
Lanning did it himself.

706
01:01:29,954 --> 01:01:32,995
What happened to you?

707
01:01:33,161 --> 01:01:35,815
Headed back to the station

708
01:01:35,816 --> 01:01:38,838
normal day, normal life...

709
01:01:38,839 --> 01:01:42,125
driver of a semi fell asleep at the wheel.

710
01:01:42,126 --> 01:01:43,740
Average guy...

711
01:01:43,741 --> 01:01:47,581
wife and kids... you know,
working a double...

712
01:01:47,701 --> 01:01:49,191
not the devil...

713
01:01:49,232 --> 01:01:53,086
the car he hit, the driver's
name was Harold Lloyd.

714
01:01:53,087 --> 01:01:54,607
Like the film star?

715
01:01:54,687 --> 01:01:56,670
No relation.

716
01:01:56,671 --> 01:01:58,726
He was killed instantly.

717
01:01:58,727 --> 01:02:03,296
But his 12 year old
was in the passenger seat.

718
01:02:03,297 --> 01:02:08,319
Never really met her...
can't forget her face though.

719
01:02:12,073 --> 01:02:15,001
Sarah.

720
01:02:15,002 --> 01:02:19,325
This was of hers.
She wanted to be a dentist.

721
01:02:19,326 --> 01:02:23,321
The hell kind of a 12 year old
wants to be a dentist?

722
01:02:23,322 --> 01:02:29,272
Ya, um, the truck smashed our cars together

723
01:02:29,273 --> 01:02:32,802
and pushed us into the river.

724
01:02:32,803 --> 01:02:37,792
I mean, metal gets pretty
pliable at those speeds.

725
01:02:37,793 --> 01:02:41,546
She's pinned, I'm pinned,
the water's coming in.

726
01:02:41,587 --> 01:02:48,032
I'm a cop so...
I already know everybody's dead.

727
01:02:48,033 --> 01:02:52,932
Just a few more minutes
before we figure it out.

728
01:02:52,933 --> 01:02:58,098
NS4 was passing by, saw the accident
and jumped in water.

729
01:02:58,099 --> 01:03:01,039
You are in danger.

730
01:03:03,913 --> 01:03:07,931
Save her, save the girl!
Save her!

731
01:03:23,694 --> 01:03:27,417
But I, um... it didn't.

732
01:03:27,418 --> 01:03:29,966
Saved me.

733
01:03:32,641 --> 01:03:34,927
The robot's brain is a difference engine.

734
01:03:34,928 --> 01:03:36,669
It's reading vital signs
that must have calculated that...

735
01:03:36,735 --> 01:03:41,647
It did...
I was the logical choice.

736
01:03:41,648 --> 01:03:45,386
Calculated that I had 45% chance of survival.

737
01:03:45,387 --> 01:03:48,395
Sarah had only an 11% chance.

738
01:03:49,841 --> 01:03:53,005
I was somebody's baby.

739
01:03:54,459 --> 01:03:57,521
11% is more than enough.

740
01:03:58,437 --> 01:04:02,184
Human being would have known that.

741
01:04:02,185 --> 01:04:05,955
Robots... nothing here...
just lights and clockwork.

742
01:04:05,956 --> 01:04:10,035
Go ahead and you
trust them if you want to.

743
01:04:10,036 --> 01:04:12,052
Let's go.

744
01:04:17,119 --> 01:04:19,998
I don't understand,
Lanning wrote the laws.

745
01:04:19,999 --> 01:04:22,832
Why would he build a robot
who could break them?

746
01:04:22,833 --> 01:04:25,041
Hansel and Gretel.

747
01:04:25,042 --> 01:04:26,141
What?

748
01:04:26,176 --> 01:04:28,236
Two kids, lost in the forest...

749
01:04:28,237 --> 01:04:29,793
